{{for|the murder victim|Barbara Ann Hackmann Taylor}} '''Barbara Taylor''' is a Canadian-born historian based in the United Kingdom, specialising in the [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]], [[gender studies]] and the history of [[subjectivity]]. She is Professor of [[Humanities]] at [[Queen Mary, University of London]].{{r|qmul}}
Taylor has written a biography of [[Mary Wollstonecraft]], the early English feminist and republican,{{r|guardian|additional}} and continues to speak on her life, for example in 2009 at [[Newington Green Unitarian Church]] as part of the celebrations of the 250th anniversary of Wollstonecraft's birth.
With psychologist [[Adam Phillips (psychologist)|Adam Phillips]], Taylor is the coauthor of ''On Kindness'' (2009).{{r|nyt|guardian2|times}} Taylor's memoir ''The Last Asylum: A Memoir of Madness in Our Times'', describing her years at [[Friern Hospital]], was published in 2014.{{r|star|telegraph|wapo|artla}} It was a finalist for the 2015 [[RBC Taylor Prize]].{{r|taylor}}
