{{coord|52|33|05|N|13|32|47|E|type:landmark|display=title}}
[[File:Sintistein parkfriedhof marzahn 2003.jpg|right|200px|thumb|Memorial stone on the nearby cemetery, commemorating the camp.]]
'''Berlin-Marzahn Rastplatz''' was a camp set up for [[Romani people]] in the [[Berlin]] [[suburb]] of [[Marzahn]] by [[Nazi]] authorities.

The Nazis used the [[Nuremberg Laws]] related to social misfits, vagabonds, and criminals as a means to intimidate and arrest Romani and Sinti Gypsies in Germany.<ref name=":1" /> At 4 a.m. on 16 July 1936, prior to the opening of the [[1936 Berlin Olympics]], police arrested 600 Gypsies<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://hdl.handle.net/2027/pur1.32754066664065?urlappend=%3Bseq=1|title=Sinti & Roma : victims of the Nazi era, 1933-19 [i.e. 1945].|website=HathiTrust|access-date=2017-05-02}}</ref> in [[Greater Berlin]] and forcibly relocated them via 130 caravans<ref name=":0" /> to Marzahn, an open field in eastern Berlin sandwiched between a cemetery and a sewage dump.<ref name="ushmm">{{cite web|url=http://www.ushmm.org/wlc/article.php?lang=en&ModuleId=10005482|title=Persecution of Roma (Gypsies) in Prewar Germany, 1933-1939|date=2008-05-20|publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|accessdate=2008-07-08}}</ref><ref name="friedlaender">{{cite book|last= Friedlaender|first=Saul|title=Nazi Germany and the Jews|publisher=HarperCollins|location=New York|year=1997|volume=I: The Years of Persecution, 1933-1939|url=http://www.nizkor.org/ftp.cgi/camps/ftp.py?camps//marzahn//marzahn-established}} Friedlaender puts the date of the initial arrests at May 1936, not July</ref>
Upon arrival the men and women were separated and taken for medical inspection. From there, prisoners were either deemed fit to work or unfit. Those that were deemed unfit were sent to execution.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Atrocities, Massacres, and War Crimes|last=Mikaberidze|first=Alexander|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2013|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>  Later, the prison would be surrounded by [[barbed wire]] and prisoners were subject to forced labour in armament plants.<ref name="ushmm" /><ref name="friedlaender" /> The camp also led to involuntary sterilization and loss of citizenship to the Gypsy prisoners as they were classified as aliens (Non-Aryans).<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Milton|first=Sybil|date=1990-01-01|title=The Context of the Holocaust|jstor=1430708|journal=German Studies Review|volume=13|issue=2|pages=269–283|doi=10.2307/1430708}}</ref>

Eventually, the men from Marzahn would be sent to [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp]] (in 1938), and women and children were sent to [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] (in 1943).<ref name="ushmm" />

