{{Infobox book | italic title = <!--(see above)--> | name = Curse on This country:The Rebellious Army of Imperial Japan | image = Curse_on_This_Country_cover.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | author = [[Danny Orbach]] | audio_read_by = | title_orig = | orig_lang_code = | title_working = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = English | series = | release_number = | subject = | genre = | set_in = | published = | publisher = [[Cornell University Press]] | publisher2 = | pub_date = 2016 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 384 | awards = | isbn = 978-1-5017-0528-1 | isbn_note = | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | native_wikisource = | wikisource = | notes = | exclude_cover = | website = }}
'''''Curse on This Country: The Rebellious Army of Imperial Japan''''' is a 2016 history book by [[Danny Orbach]], a professor at [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem|Hebrew University]] in [[Jerusalem]]. It deals with a variety of rebellions by the Imperial military though the 19th and early 20th century. It argues that a culture of disobedience and rebellion existed in the Japanese army, deriving from the tradition of the shishi (warriors of high aspirations), rebellious samurai active in the 1860s. It preserved itself and expanded over decades, due to political conditions, historical circumstances and the institutional development of the [[Imperial Japanese Army]]. It was fed by enduring leniency to right-wing rebels as long as their motives were "pure".{{fact|date=December 2017}}
The book is tracing this culture of military insubordination through its earliest manifestations, exploring such incidents as the [[Japanese invasion of Taiwan (1874)|Taiwan Expedition]] (1874), the [[Satsuma Rebellion]] (1877), and the assassinations of [[Empress Myeongseong|Queen Min]] (1895) and [[Zhang Zuolin]] (1928), as well as terrorist activities of group such as the [[Sakurakai|Cherry Blossom Society]] (1931) and the Young Officers Movement (1936). Finally, it argues that the Japanese Army's culture of disobedience helped to push the country towards unbridled imperialism, entanglement in China and finally the [[Pacific War]].<ref> Tsuchiyama, Ray [http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2017/04/22/books/book-reviews/curse-country-rebellious-army-imperial-japan-insubordination-road-wwii/ ‘Curse on This Country: The Rebellious Army of Imperial Japan’: Of insubordination and the road to WWII April 22, 2017] ''[[Japan Times]]'' Retrieved April 24, 2017 </ref><ref> [http://www.andrewlownie.co.uk/authors/danny-orbach/books/curse-on-this-country Curse of This Country] Retrieved April 25, 2017 </ref><ref> [http://oianews.com/curse-on-this-country-the-rebellious-army-of-imperial-japan-of-insubordination-and-the-road-to-wwii 'Curse on This Country: The Rebellious Army of Imperial Japan': Of insubordination and the road to WWII April 23, 2017] ''oianews'' Retrieved April 25, 2017 </ref>
