[[File:DesankaKovacevic-Kojic.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Desanka Kovačević-Kojić]]
'''Desanka Kovačević-Kojić''' ([[Serbian language|Serbian]] [[Cyrillic]]: '''Десанка Ковачевић-Којић''') is a [[Serbs|Serbian]] historian, a specialist in the medieval history of [[Serbia]] and [[Bosnia]], and in particular urban history, trade and commercial relations. Born on October 3, 1925, in [[Sarajevo]], then a part of the [[Kingdom of Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes]], she escaped from Sarajevo in 1993 after the [[Bosnian War|civil war]] started and settled in [[Belgrade]], where she is today a member of the [[SANU|Serbian Academy of Science and Arts]]. Before the [[Bosnian War|civil war]] in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia]], she was elected a member of [[Academy of Sciences and Arts of Bosnia and Herzegovina|ANUBiH]].

Desanka Kovačević-Kojić studied history at the  [[University of Belgrade]] [[University of Belgrade Faculty of Philosophy|Faculty of Philosophy]], graduating in 1950. She was professor at the [[University of Sarajevo]], and since 1993 has worked in the Institute for History in Belgrade. With Radovan Samardžić, during the 1960s she spent a year in [[Paris]], specializing in history at the seminary of [[Fernand Braudel]]. She has published several monographs and more than a hundred studies and articles in the Serbian and French languages.

==Selected works==
