'''Frederick George "Fred" Hall-Jones''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|OBE|size=85%}} (4 July 1891 &ndash; 28 January 1982) was a New Zealand lawyer, historian and community leader. He was born in Scarborough just south of [[Timaru]], [[South Canterbury]], New Zealand on 4 July 1891.<ref name="DNZB Hall-Jones">{{DNZB|last=Hall-Jones|first=John|id=5h4|title=Frederick George Hall-Jones|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref> He was the son of [[William Hall-Jones]].<ref name="DNZB Hall-Jones" />

He was appointed an [[Order of the British Empire|Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] in the [[1957 Birthday Honours|1957 Queen's Birthday Honours]], for services in community affairs and as an historian in [[Southland, New Zealand|Southland]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=41091 |date=13 June 1957 |page=3412 |supp=y }}</ref> His son, [[John Hall-Jones]], was an [[Otorhinolaryngology|otolaryngologist]] (i.e. a doctor who specialised in the ear, nose, and throat or ENT region), author and historian of southern New Zealand.<ref name=stimes>{{cite news|first=Michael |last=Fallow |title=Southern historian John Hall-Jones dies |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/southland-times/news/74293425/Southern-historian-John-Hall-Jones-dies |work=[[Southland Times]] |date=2015-11-23 |accessdate=2015-12-15}}</ref>

