'''Joseph C. Burke''' (1932 – August 3, 2018) was an American educator and academic<ref>[https://www.plattsburgh.edu/news/news-archive/former-suny-plattsburgh-president-joseph-burke-dies-at-86.html Former SUNY Plattsburgh President Joseph Burke Dies at 86]</ref> best known for serving as President of the [[State University of New York at Plattsburgh]] and Acting Chancellor of the [[State University of New York]].
Burke earned a bachelor's degree in History and Philosophy from [[Bellarmine University|Bellarmine College]] and Master's and Ph.D. degrees in Legal History from [[Indiana University, Bloomington]].
Burke began his career at [[Ohio Wesleyan University]] and [[Duquesne University]].<ref> {{cite web |url= http://www.rockinst.org/research/education/higher_education/2column.aspx?id=716 |title= Program Areas: Higher Education |accessdate= 2008-04-13 |publisher= [http://www.rockinst.org/ The Nelson A. Rockefeller Institute of Government] }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> He assumed the position of Academic Vice President [[Loyola College (Montreal)]] and negotiated its merger with [[Sir George Williams University]] to form [[Concordia University (Montreal)|Concordia University]] in 1974. He then moved to the [[State University of New York at Plattsburgh]], serving as its President for twelve years.<ref> {{cite web |url= http://www.plattsburgh.edu/president/past.php |title= Past Presidents and Principals of SUNY Plattsburgh |accessdate= 2008-04-13 |publisher= [[State University of New York at Plattsburgh]] Office of the President }}</ref> Burke became Provost and Vice Chancellor for Academic Affairs of SUNY in 1986 and was asked to assume the chancellorship when his predecessor resigned due to failing health.<ref>{{Cite news | title= Interim Chancellor for SUNY | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 27, 1994 | url = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE6DC173AF934A15751C0A962958260 | accessdate = 2008-04-13 }}</ref>
Burke was a Senior Fellow with the Rockefeller Institute's Higher Education Program until his passing in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockinst.org/staff/1column.aspx?id=242&ekmensel=14_submenu_0_link_1 |title=Staff |accessdate=2008-04-13 |publisher=[http://www.rockinst.org/ The Nelson A. Rockefeller Institute of Government] |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080420060615/http://www.rockinst.org/staff/1column.aspx?id=242 |archivedate=April 20, 2008 }} </ref>
SUNY Plattsburgh's Burke Gallery is named after him.
